Scope of the Reference Implementation

This reference implementation includes:

ledger structures

transaction models

resolution logic

demo scripts

outputs and reference outputs

validation traces

supporting artifacts provided in this release

ORL defines a deterministic structural ledger model in which correctness emerges from structural completeness and consistency rather than from transaction order or time.

The reference implementation establishes the following conceptual model:

resolve(structure) ->
    accept if complete and consistent
    remain incomplete if required parts are missing
    abstain if structure is conflicting

Final correctness emerges when:

structural_validity = complete AND consistent


What the Reference Implementation Demonstrates

• ledger correctness from incomplete and fragmented inputs
• independence from transaction ordering
• independence from timestamps and synchronized clocks for correctness
• bounded information sharing between independent nodes
• deterministic convergence across multiple nodes
• structural resolution with safe incompleteness
• conflict handling through abstention
• reproducible and verifiable resolution outcomes

The reference implementation is provided to demonstrate the feasibility of structure-based ledger correctness without reliance on order, sequence, or synchronization as the primary correctness authority.


Conformance

An implementation is considered compatible with the ORL reference model if it preserves the core structural principles demonstrated by the implementation, including:

• correctness derived from structural completeness and consistency
• independence from transaction order as the primary correctness authority
• independence from synchronized time for correctness
• deterministic convergence across independent nodes
• reproducibility under equivalent structural inputs
• explicit handling of incomplete and conflicting states

Independent implementations are permitted and encouraged.

Conformance is determined by observable behavior of the system under equivalent
structural inputs, not by internal implementation details.


